item.detail:
The winbase.h include file contains the following incorrect prototype: 

PVOID WINAPI InterlockedCompareExchange(PVOID*,PVOID,PVOID); 

It should be: 

PVOID WINAPI InterlockedCompareExchangePointer(PVOID*,PVOID,PVOID); 

and the following prototype is missing: 

LONG WINAPI InterlockedCompareExchange(LPLONG,LONG,LONG); 

(or vice versa depending on how you look at it).

There should be some means for the file stream classes in C++ to open any existing file on a user's computer, or create any file with a valid name. As far as I know, the only way to open a file whose name falls outside of the system codepage is to use the corresponding "short name" (8.3), but not all filesystems have short names (e.g. on NTFS they can be disabled.) As long as ifstream has this limitation, it just can't be used in desktop programs that take internationalization seriously, so adding some sort of Unicode support would really help. 

Some options for adding Unicode support: 
- if the file name passed on the constructor or to open() begins with a "*", discard the "*" and interpret the rest of the string as UTF-8; 
- add a constructor that takes wchar_t* ; 
- add a constructor that takes a file descriptor; 
- use an environment setting or a global variable to decide if names passed to ifstream should be interpreted as UTF-8 or as system codepage; 

All these suggestions have drawbacks, but to me they all look better than the current situation.

